// ... existing code ...
<h3>Well guess what, sweetie:</h3>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<p>You. Are. Over-designing. Look at this. It's a website. Why do you need to animate a trendy-ass banner flag when I hover over that useless thing? You spent hours on it and added 80 kilobytes to your site, and some friend jabbing at it on their iPad with fat fingers will never see that. Not to mention people with disabilities will never see that, but they don't see any of your other stuff either.</p>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<p>You never knew it, but this is your perfect website. Here's why.</p>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<h2>It's so lightweight</h2>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<p>This entire page weighs less than the gradient-meshed facebook logo on your Wordpress site. Did you seriously load 100kb of jQuery UI just so you could animate the background color of a div? You loaded all 7 fontfaces of a webfont just so you could say "Hi." at 100px height at the beginning of your site? You're something else.</p>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<h2>It's responsive</h2>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<p>You silly. You thought you needed media queries to be responsive, but no. Responsive means that it responds to whatever screensize it's viewed on. This site doesn't care if you're on an iMac or a Tamagotchi.</p>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<h2>It works</h2>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<p>Look at this. You can read it ... that is, if you can read. It makes sense. It has hierarchy. It's using HTML5 tags so you and your browser know what's in this site. That's semantics.</p>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<p>It has content on the screen. Your site has three bylines and link to your dribbble account, but you spread it over 7 full screens and make me click some button to show me how cool the jQuery ScrollTo plugin is.</p>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<p>Cross-browser compatibility? Load this in IE6. I dare you.</p>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<h2>This is a website. Look at it. You've never seen one before.</h2>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<p>Like the person who's never grown out their beard has no idea what their true natural state is, you have no idea what a website is. All you have ever seen are bastardizations of what should be text communicating a message. This is a real, naked website. Look at it. It's beautiful.</p>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<h3>Yes, this is satire, you dear</h3>
// ... existing code ...
// ... existing code ...
<p>I'm not actually saying your site should look like this. What I'm saying is that all the problems we have with websites are ones we create ourselves. Websites aren't broken by default, they are functional, high-performing, and accessible. You make them not so.</p>
